07379nam a22009375i 9780812200645DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102004pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122006457 a10.9783/97808122006452doi  a(DE-B1597)448916  a(OCoLC)979575931  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ1032b.C67 2005 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a306.84/5/09522200aCross-Border Marriages :bGender and Mobility in Transnational Asia /ced. by Nicole Constable. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1. Introduction: Cross-Border Marriages, Gendered Mobility, and Global Hyperqamy -- tChapter 2. Cross-Border Hypergamy? Marriage Exchanges in a Transnational Hakka Community -- tChapter 3. Cautionary Tales: Marriage Strategies, State Discourse, and Women's Agency in a Naxi Village in Southwestern China -- tChapter 4. Marrying out of Place: Hmong/Miao Women Across and Beyond China -- tChapter 5. Marrying Up and Marrying Down: The Paradoxes of Marital Mobility for Chosonjok Brides in South Korea -- tChapter 6. A Failed Attempt at Transnational Marriage: Maternal Citizenship in a Globalizing South Korea -- tChapter 7. Tripartite Desires: Filipina-Japanese Marriages and Fantasies of Transnational Traversal -- tChapter 8. Clashing Dreams in the Vietnamese Diaspora: Highly Educated Overseas Brides and Low-Wage U.S. Husbands -- tChapter 9. A Tale of Two Marriages: International Matchmaking and Gendered Mobility -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIlluminating how international marriages are negotiated, arranged, and experienced, Cross-Border Marriages is the first book to chart marital migrations involving women and men of diverse national, ethnic, and class backgrounds. The migrations studied here cross geographical borders of provinces, rural-urban borders within nation-states, and international boundaries, including those of China, Japan, South Korea, India, Vietnam, the Philippines, the United States, and Canada. Looking at assumptions about the connection between international marriages and poverty, opportunism, and women's mobility, the book draws attention to ideas about global patterns of inequality that are thought to pressure poor women to emigrate to richer countries, while simultaneously suggesting the limitations of such views.Breaking from studies that regard the international bride as a victim of circumstance and the mechanisms of international marriage as traffic in commodified women, these essays challenge any simple idea of global hypergamy and present a nuanced understanding where a variety of factors, not the least of which is desire, come into play. Indeed, most contemporary marriage-scapes involve women who relocate in order to marry; rarely is it the men. But Nicole Constable and the volume contributors demonstrate that, contrary to popular belief, these brides are not necessarily poor, nor do they categorically marry men who are above them on the socioeconomic ladder.Although often women may appear to be moving "up" from a less developed country to a more developed one, they do not necessarily move higher on the chain of economic resources. Complicating these and other assumptions about international marriages, the essays in this volume draw from interviews and rich ethnographic materials to examine women's and men's agency, their motivations for marriage, and the importance of familial pressures and obligations, cultural imaginings, fantasies, and desires, in addition to personal and economic factors.Border-crossing marriages are significant for what they reveal about the intersection of local and global processes in the everyday lives of women and men whose marital opportunities variably yield both rich possibilities and bitter disappointments.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIntercountry marriagezAsia. 0aIntercountry marriage. 0aSocial mobility. 0aWomenzAsia. 4aFolklore. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.1 aAbelmann, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCam Thai, Hung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChao, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConstable, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConstable, Nicole, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFreeman, Caren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Hyunhee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOxfeld, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchein, Louisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSuzuki, Nobue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Social Sciencesz978311041361808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220064540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812200645423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812200645.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041361-8  Penn